R. Hollander [a cura di], ^Studi americani su Dante~, Milano, Angeli,
1989, pp. 123-25). Le anime si muovono senza riflessione (|lo 'mperch$e
non sanno~), ma non perch$e siano incerte sulla direzione da prendere,
ma perch$e confidano nella loro guida: si tratta di "un movimento
dettato dalla fede, piuttosto che dalla conoscenza" (Singleton). Si
legga Lansing: "And what interpretation could be more pertinent to the
context? Has Vergil not just counselled the pilgrim, quite forcefully,
on the limits of natural reason, and that certain truths, the nature
of the Trinity for one, must be accepted by act of faith? It was Dante's
momentary fear of being abandoned by his leader which occasioned Vergil's
mild rebuke opening with the interrogative |Perch$e pur diffidi?~
(v. 22) and closing on the exhortative |State contenti, umana gente,
al ^quia~~ (v. 37). The act of restored faith finds its fulfillment in
the Excommunicate, and the simile effectively alludes to it by revealing
